en challenged the cultures into which they married and shaped their new courtly environments. Through the lens of medieval gender and postcolonial theory, Exchanges in Exoticism demonstrates how the process of cultural exchange – and empire building – extends well beyond our traditional assumptions about gender roles in the medieval Mediterranean.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311049093008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2019z978311065878140uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266136340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442661363423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442661363.jpg  a978-3-11-049093-0  UTP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065878-1  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2019c2014d2019  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK